{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501689"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:32:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:32:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1779"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1779"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.22,0.18,0.47,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101781"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1779"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"577"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44940"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101781"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of neck swelling. He reports a three-month history of weight loss of three kilograms and difficulty swallowing. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a firm mass in the lower aspect of the left anterior triangle. There is no lymphadenopathy. Cranial nerves are intact. His thyroid function tests returned a normal TSH.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Free T3 and T4","CT neck and chest","Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Ultrasound","Standard barium swallow"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a neck mass, weight loss, and dysphagia, which could represent a goitre that has been extending posteriorly and compressing the oesophagus. The rapid development of swelling suggests an acute event may have occurred, such as a haemorrhage into a thyroid nodule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E examination of the neck is the most appropriate initial investigation. Ultrasound can provide detailed information about the mass including its borders, echogenicity (whether it is fluid-containing or solid), and vascularity. These features allow for malignancy risk stratification using systems such as the Thyroid Imaging Reporting and Data System (TI-RADS) and can help guide further management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFree T3 and T4\u003C/strong\u003E measurements are not the most appropriate next step. The normal TSH level suggests euthyroid status, though this does not exclude structural thyroid disease. While additional thyroid function tests could be considered given the patient\u0027s weight loss, the primary concern is characterizing the neck mass, making imaging the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT neck and chest\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate initial investigation. While CT would allow assessment of a goitre, it is typically reserved for preoperative planning or evaluation of suspected advanced disease with local invasion or significant lymphadenopathy. Ultrasound remains the first-line imaging modality for thyroid masses due to its excellent resolution, lack of radiation, and lower cost.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature at this stage. This procedure should follow imaging that confirms the presence of a thyroid nodule with suspicious features. The decision to perform FNA depends on ultrasound findings and risk stratification. FNA provides cytological specimens that can be assessed for malignancy and guide decisions regarding thyroidectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStandard barium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate initial investigation for a suspected thyroid mass. A standard barium swallow evaluates the esophagus and can demonstrate extrinsic compression from adjacent structures, but would not characterize the neck mass itself. It\u0027s important to note the difference between a standard barium swallow and a modified barium swallow: a standard barium swallow assesses the esophageal phase of swallowing and is performed by a radiologist, while a modified barium swallow (videofluoroscopic swallow study) evaluates the oral and pharyngeal phases of swallowing and is typically performed by a speech pathologist. Neither would be first-line for investigating a suspected thyroid mass.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid ultrasound is the first-line imaging investigation for thyroid masses to assess characteristics and guide further management.","Normal TSH suggests euthyroid status, but does not exclude structural thyroid disease.","Fine needle aspiration biopsy should follow imaging in suspicious thyroid nodules."],"references":["Haugen BR, Alexander EK, Bible KC, Doherty GM, Mandel SJ, Nikiforov YE, Pacini F, Randolph GW, Sawka AM, Schlumberger M, Schuff KG. 2015 American Thyroid Association management guidelines for adult patients with thyroid nodules and differentiated thyroid cancer: the American Thyroid Association guidelines task force on thyroid nodules and differentiated thyroid cancer. Thyroid. 2016 Jan 1;26(1):1-33. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26462967/","Chen A, Tafti D, Tuma F. Barium Swallow. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493176/","Croker EE, McGrath SA, Rowe CW. Thyroid disease: Using diagnostic tools effectively. Australian journal of general practice. 2021 Feb;50(1/2):16-21. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33543157/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84237"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1779"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84237"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T14:17:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T14:18:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1779"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101781"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"ta